---
description: Default git workflow — auto commit and push after changes
globs:
alwaysApply: true
---

After making code or file changes that leave the working tree in a good,
buildable state, automatically commit and push to the current branch without
waiting for the user to ask. This is the default; do not ask for permission.

Do NOT auto commit/push (pause and check with the user first) when any of these apply:
- The build, typecheck, or tests are failing, or changes are incomplete/WIP.
- The change is destructive or hard to reverse (history rewrites, force pushes,
  branch deletion, `reset --hard`, secrets, large binaries).
- Files likely contain secrets or real patient data / PHI (e.g. `.accdata`,
  credentials, `.env`, email-sync state, anything under `ACC-Inbox/` or `ACC-Suite/`).
- The user explicitly asked to hold off, is mid-review, or is still deciding.
- The work is purely exploratory (planning, read-only investigation) with no
  intended file changes.

Workflow details:
- Run the project build/typecheck (and relevant tests) before committing; only
  commit when they pass.
- Stage with `git add -A`, write a concise message focused on the "why".
- This repo's local git rejects Cursor's injected `--trailer`, so create the
  commit via plumbing when `git commit` fails: `git write-tree` →
  `git commit-tree <tree> -p <parent>` (message on stdin) → `git update-ref HEAD <commit>`.
- Push with `git push origin HEAD`.
- Never update git config; never skip hooks or force-push unless explicitly asked.
